    "title": "Interested but not Engaged: How Europe's Media Cover Brexit",
    "link": "https://reutersinstitute.politics.ox.ac.uk/our-research/interested-not-engaged-how-europes-media-cover-brexit",
    "pubDate": "2018-07-01T23:01:00.000Z",
    "content": "<html><head></head><body><span>Interested but not Engaged: How Europe's Media Cover Brexit</span>\n<span><span>Archie</span></span>\n<span><time datetime=\"2018-07-02T00:01:00+01:00\" title=\"Monday, July 2, 2018 - 00:01\">Mon, 07/02/2018 - 00:01</time>\n</span>\n\n            <div class=\"field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field--item\"><h6><span><span>DOI: 10.60625/risj-9vzf-5a49</span></span></h6>\n\n<p><span><span>What do the media of other EU member countries consider to be important as the UK negotiates being the first country to&nbsp;leave the EU? How much and what kind of national self-interest does the Brexit decision trigger? What do European media think about Brexit&nbsp;and the UK’s way of dealing with it? These are some of the questions that <a href=\"https://reutersinstitute.politics.ox.ac.uk/people/dr-alexandra-borchardt\">Alexandra Borchardt</a>, <a href=\"https://twitter.com/_FelixSimon_\">Felix M. Simon</a> and <a href=\"https://twitter.com/dbironzo?lang=en\">Diego Bironzo</a> answer in this Reuters Institute and Prime Research report.</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span><span><span>Brexit is less than 300 days away and, perhaps unsurprisingly, European media take great interes</span></span></span></p></div></body></html>",
